From aca4a37f78fadc6f41a992e256630fc2f21c9f5b Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Quenchforge Contributors <maintainers@cerid-ai.com>
Date: Sun, 17 May 2026 13:00:00 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] metal: norm + softmax fallback kernels for non-Apple GPUs
 (v0.7.1 partial)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Adds fallback Metal kernels for `kernel_norm_fuse_impl` (LayerNorm) and
`kernel_soft_max{,_4}` (bidirectional-attention softmax) that use
fixed-size function-local threadgroup memory and pure threadgroup tree-
reductions instead of `simd_sum` / `simd_max` + dynamic threadgroup
memory passed as an entry-point parameter. The dispatchers in
`ggml-metal-device.cpp::pipeline_norm` and `pipeline_soft_max` now
select the `_fb` suffix variant when `has_simdgroup_reduction == false`.

Mechanism: combination of (a) the AMD simd-group reduction divergence
covered by patch 0001, and (b) the Metal-compiler dynamic-threadgroup-
memory barrier-ordering bug documented at gfx-rs/wgpu#4500. The
upstream kernels hit both at once.

The fallback kernels:
- Allocate threadgroup memory as a fixed-size local array
  (`threadgroup float local_buf[1024]`) — function-local, not an
  entry-point parameter, so the compiler bug doesn't apply.
- Perform reductions via threadgroup tree-reduce with explicit
  barriers between halving passes. Mathematically equivalent to
  the upstream `simd_sum` two-level reduction.

Apple Silicon is unaffected: `has_simdgroup_reduction == true` on
Apple7+, so the dispatcher selects the original (faster) kernels.

PARTIAL FIX. Measured 2026-05-17 on Vega II:
- Pre-patch identical "hello" same batch: cos_sim 0.07
- Post-patch identical "hello" same batch: cos_sim 0.29
- Pre-patch two separate "hello" calls: cos_sim 0.15
- Post-patch two separate "hello" calls: cos_sim 0.06
- CPU route (--gpu-layers 0): cos_sim 1.0000 (reference)

The norm/softmax fallback restores those specific kernels'
determinism, but matmul kernels (`kernel_mul_mv_t_t`,
`kernel_mul_mv_q*_f32`, etc.) ALSO use `simd_sum` and remain broken.
Production stays on the v0.7.0 CPU-route fix until those are also
fallback-patched (v0.8.0 candidate).

Signed-off-by: Quenchforge Contributors <maintainers@cerid-ai.com>
